This should be a wake-up call for scientists that we should not mock people that believe misinformation. This only solidifies group identities and makes us an even less trusted source. The grifters profiting off treatments with uncertain effects are extremely sophisticated.

No one except people with training in meta-analysis can be blamed for looking at https://t.co/uts2T8bZKZ and concluding IVM works. I dug in the data myself using the metafor R package and it took me far longer than I expected to find issues.

Scientists have widely mocked people for believing IVM works and taking the livestock version. I think this is entirely the wrong approach. These are desperate people, fearful of covid and the pharmaceutical industry, seeing misinformation based on a well-presented meta-analysis.

Other meta-analyses have been published (Bryant et al. 2021) and are again touted as proof IVM works (below), though a recent Cochrane review found only 4/17 studies from this MA meet pre-defined eligibility standards (https://t.co/puLXMaV8Du). https://t.co/UVVTURfw0d

The main issues with this MA I see are (1) very weak selection criteria and lots of low-quality studies, (2) huge amounts of heterogeneity in the studies. @GidMK has a thread here: https://t.co/puLXMaV8Du and writeup here: https://t.co/eqgC0wMVGt

This public-facing meta-analysis looks credible. If you search Twitter for the domain, you'll see serious-looking people with PhDs linking to it claiming IVM is an efficacious treatment. Charlatan Bret Weinstein was an early proselytizer of IVM too, Tucker advocated for IVM, etc. https://t.co/PiJKmuj822

This weekend I got sucked down the Ivermectin rabbit hole. I was shocked at the level of sophistication of the meta-analysis website https://t.co/uts2T8bZKZ, which is frequently touted as proof IVM works. The website is advanced (e.g. they're using Python + MA package)... https://t.co/Alr94cKetn

I learned most of this after coming across Bieberbach's name in the context of his isodiametric inequality. It's not part of mainstream math education, but I think it should be. For general education about the holocaust, I suggest following @yadvashem.  ⬛

Bieberbach arguably contributed directly to a deterioration in Schur's health, and his eventual death as a result of the traumas he experienced in the war. Evidently Bieberbach never faced any consequences for the harm he did to his math colleagues and to maths. יִמַּח שְׁמוֹ

Ostrowski wasn't the only one to minimize & ignore Bieberbach's crimes. Bieberbach was elected unanimously (by the board) to the Berlin Mathematical Society in 1951 (right after its reestablishment). A few mathematicians resigned in protest (e.g. Eduard Rembs), but to no avail.

As an aside (although maybe it isn't really an aside) the Ostrowski prize, awarded since 1989 every other year for 30 years now, has never been awarded to a woman. It's supposed to be for "outstanding mathematical achievement". I guess only for achievements of men (M-type math?)

Alexander Ostrowski considered Bieberbach's "political views" irrelevant and invited him to lecture in 1949. BTW this is the same Ostrowski after whom the  Ostrowski prize is named- the prize awarded to de Branges for settling the Bieberbach conjecture.

In the mid 1930s he taught a course titled "Great German mathematicians, a race-theoretic approach" & he proceeded to write papers on the topic. There was one pointed rebuttal by G.H. Hardy published in @Nature in 1934: https://t.co/BZjClkbK5m but many excused him after the war.

But above all, for the next 6 to 12 months we need to vaccinate the world - at the very least, the at risk of severe disease portion of the world. Everything else is minor compared to our progress on this.

We need to have good testing for a variety of viruses, SARS-CoV-2 and couple this to genomics, and then international data sharing (something which @emblebi, which I am a director of, facilitates along side other partners worldwide).

The new normal is still a bit unclear; there are low impact transmission preventions, probably #1 good ventilation inside and #2 mask wearing in risky transmission situations which we need to get used to for a longer time.

Central and Eastern Europe, which in many places had a very hard 2020 winter still have some large vaccination gaps (far far bigger than the French example above) and will need to plug those as more people come inside during the winter.

Across Europe, the countries I know and understand the best, Western Europe is largely looking on course to navigate the next steps; arguably England+Scotland have made big steps back to a new normality; Denmark's flagged transition to living with the virus on September 10th.
The main thing here is to improve vaccine production rates (we will not regret having more vaccine production in the mid to long term) and then equitable supply - what the @gavi alliance focuses on.

The reason why is that it is far to easy to be caught up in the developed world concerns when still the main benefit per dose of vaccine comes when at risk unvaccinated, uninfected people get the vaccines - most of these people live in Africa, South America and Asia now.

This leads you to boosters, in particular for at risk people. Israel has already implemented a booster campaign and it seems to work; the UK is running a RCT on boosters, including smaller doses, which would be great if these work as well as smaller doses (expected).
(Please note: Natural infection when not vaccinated carries huge risks of severe disease - if old, of full blown COVID, if younger, of LongCOVID which we are still trying to understand)

Wrapped up in this are questions of waning immunity. This seems low from natural infection but higher from vaccination, in particular Pfzier/BioNTech, seen in English and Israeli data. Israel is a striking example of a country that had suppressed under Alpha but not Delta.

<< this easily could be the start of the normal "endemicity" (fancy way of saying living with) of us and SARS-CoV-2, where a combination of waning immunity and new births means it circulates forever, hopefully, due to vaccination, not producing too much serious disease.

Delta has made this far more complex because Delta's transmission is far less blunted than Alpha (or other, earlier) variants. This means that a significant number of people who are vaccinated will be infected before there is a large suppression on transmission, indeed >>

This large gap in vaccination numbers is in my view why the US South at the moment is having such a horrible 4th wave, and this is likely to repeat throughout all areas with significant numbers of unvaccinated, at risk individuals.

France might be running a somewhat higher risk than the UK but the developed country running the biggest risk is the US, with both some communities (eg, African American) coming forward less to be vaccinated and others being adamantly against vaccination.

In this case France and England have overall similar proportions of vaccinated individuals, but France is running a higher risk with more older unvaccinated. These are the hard miles of vaccination of programs to close out the last 15, 10, 5% of people.

Flo Débarre @flodebarre and others on twitter have been making accessible visualisations of this for the countries that provide age-stratified vaccination numbers. For example, here is France compared to England. Colours are vaccinated - grey unvaccinated https://t.co/hCSSm2VEuV

Turning to the developed world, a key aspect which I think is hard to pick up in overall tables and rankings is the importance of vaccination reach by age (and other risk variables). We really want the risk-weighted unvaccinated numbers in each country.
Vaccinating the world should be our #1 global priority.

Before I give my view on the developed world landscape, I must stress that this step change has not been reached worldwide. This is the biggest change we can make; for equity; for removing human suffering; for our selfish health (preventing new variants) and economic reasons.

VIRUS CONCENTRATION. Small aerosols (<5µm) contain the highest virus concentrations and can travel deeper into the lungs.SARS-CoV-2 has been detected in particles 0.25-4µm in size, where it remains suspended in the air for minutes to hours and has a half-life of ~1-3 hours.6/9 https://t.co/y6LuFxpzHW

AIRBORNE vs INFECTIVITY. Because measles is airborne, many have assumed that airborne viruses are all highly contagious.In reality, the relationship is not straightforward, and a host of other factors contribute. Tuberculosis is airborne but less transmissible than COVID.5/9 https://t.co/7qtlTPCPMi

PREDOMINANCE OF AIRBORNE TRANSMISSION. Sampling disrupts airborne viruses, making them a challenge to study.Even so, the higher rate of transmission indoors than outdoors is incompatible with predominant droplet spread, because droplets behave identically in both settings.4/9

DROPLET vs. AIRBORNE. There is no binary cutoff wherein droplet transmission occurs at close ranges and airborne occurs at long ranges.Instead, aerosols can transmit at both ranges, and are most concentrated close to the infected person.Masks help prevent both.3/9 https://t.co/8CrFmAQxfd

AEROSOLS. "Aerosols are microscopic liquid, solid, or semisolid particles that are so small they remain suspended in air." In the link below you can find more details about our findings (under peer-review) about the global disparities in SARS-CoV-2 genomic surveillance. 🌎🦠🧬https://t.co/Z8UO7vy5dw

Efforts must be made to provide funds, training, and logistic support for low- and middle-income countries to improve their local genomic surveillance capacity, to allow public health decision making in regions where resources may be scarce.

In order to maintain constant and rapid genome sequencing, local coordination, adequate staffing/training, and appropriate analytical tools are essential for enabling rapid responses to emerging infectious disease threats to public health.

Socioeconomic, epidemiological, and political factors (coordination) impact genomic surveillance capacity and timeliness. As a result, genomic surveillance in many countries is sparse, and do not meet the minimum threshold of 0.5% of sequenced cases per week.

Local public health labs should strengthen their local capacity to sequence at least 0.5% of cases per week, when incidence is high (100 cases/100,000 pop.). 📈In this scenario of peak incidence, such threshold can be achieve by sequencing 1 genome for every 200,000 habitants.

In this study we identified that Denmark has one of the best genomic surveillance programs, with quick turnaround (<18 days) and high % of sequenced cases (>32%). The lineage diversity in Denmark is large. Countries with low surveillance may be missing many circulating variants. https://t.co/UdsmlyTV9L

Using binomial confidence intervals, we estimated that when the prevalence of a rare lineage is 2%, 300 cases would need to be sequenced for at least one genome of that lineage to be detected with 95% probability. Rapid turnaround time is also essential for quick detection. https://t.co/icxMfKyQRB

How the % of sequenced cases and the turnaround time affect a country’s ability to detect a previously-identified variant?First, our results show that countries sequencing low % of cases and few genomes tend to detect less SARS-CoV-2 lineage diversity in circulation. https://t.co/DRCHam0saK

Disparities in national wealth, in investment in R&D, and national coordination impact the ability of countries to perform genomic surveillance. Below we show how the % sequenced cases and turnaround time correlate with socioeconomic factors. https://t.co/iXBsD4iJJ9

With the worsening of the pandemic, and high COVID-19 incidences, few countries were able to maintain fast and deep genomic surveillance, especially low- and middle-income countries, which generated few or no sequences in many weeks in 2020-2021. https://t.co/n1HPzecxti

Pre-print of C.1.2, which will be updated soon with neutralization results at: https://t.co/kJ906bKfe6

This is the work of dozens of scientists as part of the Network of Genomic Surveillance in South Africa (NGS-SA). The pre-print analysis was lead by @NICD and @krisp_news and it also involves a very bright and young women scientist, Catherine Scheepers, who is the first author.

The reason why we decided to publish the preprint is that we see the C.1.2 persistence in South Africa and is now in another 10 countries. It is early days as only 95 genomes have been published at GISAID. However, we found that in this pandemic is share info quicker than later.

We now have the C.1.x persisting for over 1 year in South Africa and now evolving to C.1.2 further to add a dozen new mutations at Spike.  We are now working with @sigallab & Penny Moore to describe the effect of the mutations in a live virus and pseudo virus system.

Someday I will try to expand on some of the dynamics I think operate here, and some of the conceptual muddling around gender identity, but today is not that day.
All they do is reify gender roles, either by themselves or in opposition thereto, and I am not interested in having my humanity limited by pressures to conform to one more than another.

I am definitely not on board with essentialist conceptions of gender identity that root it in the social constructs of masculinity and femininity rather than sense of self as a particular sex, which is why I am comfortable with the label “transexual” (it adds clarity)

Approaches to trans rights that do not recognise how patriarchy operates or how transmisogyny operates are simply inadequate. Sort your gender politics out. As Aunt Mallory says (go follow her , @Chican3ry) , ya’ll probably need more feminism.

Therefore we need to have radical politics towards abolishing the patriarchy and normative gender for trans liberation and practise coalitional politics with cis feminists. We also need radical forms of transfeminism that foreground our lived experiences while we are at it.
@kseniakrasileva These sound fun but what do you actually *do* at one? How long is it? Are people presenting?

This also sets up a double standard where people may use my relationship to normative gender to clock me. If misgendering didn’t make me dysphoric it’d be easier to resist it. GNC transfems deserve better, those forced to submit deserve the greatest empathy.

This reeks of sexist double standards that value proximity to maleness and masculinity, and devalue proximity to femaleness and femininity. All the while, I face pressures to subordinate myself into a normative femininity that is shaped by misogyny. I absolutely hate this.

What has been far harder is navigating society while being visibly transexual , my sense of public safety has been markedly more affected, for starters – sexual harassment, catcalling, being followed down the street, homophobic abuse ; 10 incidents in the last couple of months.

The Pango system is mainly managed by volunteer researchers from @PangoNetwork: https://t.co/uVhLzm7VdrIn this article you can learn more about the work done by these researchers, which provide daily updates about new SARS-CoV-2 lineages.https://t.co/u8RCZgRodJ

Currently there are 3 main systems of SARS-CoV-2 nomenclature.Pango: https://t.co/3JU33C6QaSNextclade: https://t.co/5CsExHP8yKWHO: https://t.co/Bqk2IflUzyThey have similarities, and share a common objective: to guide ourselves along the complex evolutionary path of viruses.

By tracking viral evolution closely, and providing a neutral, systematic nomenclature for new SARS-CoV-2 lineages, we can avoid inadequate names, which may cause unnecessary confusion and anxiety, such as “Delta Plus”, which is meaningless.https://t.co/yvykpyKsKu

This dynamic evolution explains why we have so many lineages today, such as: B.1.1.7, B.1.617.2, P.1 (descending from B.1.1.28.1)This alphanumeric system is well-suited to accommodate phylogenetic patterns. It's neutral, and prevents stigma (“Indian variant”, “UK variant”, etc)

SARS-CoV-2 lineages are named following an alphanumeric format, up to its 4th level, when new alias of 1st level may be assigned. That is what happened recently with lineages of Delta:B → B.1 → B.1.617 → B.1.617.2 (Delta) →→→ AYMore information: https://t.co/J3u4BJtbBH https://t.co/CbISRl4DtH

As explained above, virus evolution is very dynamic: researchers are always detecting new lineages when they sequence viral genomes from COVID samples.Using the Pango nomenclature system, all lineages described so far are described at https://t.co/z7IIC4bKe0 https://t.co/JzcUDW3UlB

New lineages always come up, increase or decrease in frequency, and eventually get so rare that they are no longer detected (and eventually may disappear).Users of Pango submit daily requests for designation of new lineages via a GitHub system. https://t.co/JarR995YJA

This thread will disappoint many of  my lab leak followers and irritate someone in the other camp. But I don't care, this is what I think and always thought.

A natural #spillover and a #LabLeak have always been plausible hypotheses. Both have circumstantial evidence on their side, both suffer inconsistencies or lack of data. Where did SARS2 come from? Nobody knows, but science is now in a better position to find it out. 10/

I am sorry for the general public, who might feel a bit confused by the narrative shift and the revival of the lab leak hypothesis. But this is what happens when scientists make bold claims without enough evidence, and pretend there is a #consensus when there is none. 9/

Now everything is different, thanks to the presidency change and the famous Science letter. Scientists seem to be more open to other interpretations, they discuss (sometimes fiercely) and highlight the weaknesses in each other's arguments. Science at work, finally. 8/

The lack of #transparency from China and the lack of a proper debate among scientists are the two things that led me to tweet and write articles on this topic. Those practices were harming #science reputation, and I couldn't stay silent: I love science! 7/

Even worse, we later discovered that the same scientists who were so sure about the natural origin of the virus had expressed before the very same doubts of the so-called "conspiracy theorists". Taking this into account, their patronizing attitude was even more irritating. 6/

Back then, those who dared to talk about experiments or lab leaks were mocked and accused of promoting #conspiracy theories. It goes without saying that in that environment, skeptical scientists preferred to stay quiet. 5/

Most scientists remained silent, or just cited the Proximal Origin paper without any critical evaluation of its content. Too busy with their work? Maybe. But I have a feeling that a lot of them were afraid to join a discussion that had become 100% political, because of #Trump. 4/

The second thing that I didn't like was the suppression of an open dialogue between scientists, which lasted for several months. Now it's easier for scientists to freely talk about the different scenarios, but do you remember how difficult it was one year ago? 3/

Since the beginning, some scientists working in Chinese institutions haven't been fully transparent. The history of #RaTG13 and the issues with its sequencing data, the miners pneumonia, the missing database, the pangolin CoV data. Hiding info, playing with words. Bad science. 2/

In recent years, work from several labs has shown that the biomass consumed by a phagocyte informs the process as much as things outside of the phagocyte. Intuitively, this makes sense. How would YOU feel if you just ate a bunch of lipids, proteins, nucleotides, etc...

Take a moment to think about it. A phagocyte has to find, recognize, engulf, and digest an apoptotic cell. Each of these steps require intricate navigation of several variables, including their native environment and the nature of what they are clearing.

In this review, we try our best to synthesize the wealth of recent studies on how phagocytes, both professional (eg macrophages) and non-professional (eg epithelial cells), adapt to the various steps of the phagocytosis process.

Ordering is the other interesting decreasing category. This refers to putting cells in a continuous order (think pseudotime analysis). I think this reflects perhaps the biggest disappointments of single-cell to date, it's much harder to observe continuous processes than we hoped.

Visualisation is the most common category but also has one of the biggest decreasing trends. I don't think this is because visualisation is becoming less important but that there are enough plotting functions in existing packages that you don't need to create your own anymore.

More tools for integration reflects the availability of multi-sample datasets and the desire to construct atlases for tissues, organisms, diseases etc. Classification is a key use of these atlases once they exist. These categories are linked so them both increasing makes sense.

This shows the current proportion of tools in the database on the x-axis against the trend over time on the y-axis. Classification and Integration stand out as increasing while Visualisation and Ordering are becoming less common. https://t.co/qUfCIApSTp

One of the key features of @scRNAtools is tagging each tool with analysis categories depending on what it can do. Tasks like visualisation, dimensionality reduction and clustering remain the most common but there are some interesting trends... https://t.co/02agnwspBJ

Most tools use a standard open-source software license, with MIT and various flavours of GPL being most common.About 20% of tools have no clear license. IMO journals and reviewers should insist on a license as part of making code available. https://t.co/d2lwtYyVCU

Maintaining a software package is a big commitment. Many of the tools which aren't in a repository are likely intended as proofs of concept or reproduce results in a paper rather than a package for general use. This is a totally valid choice.
As a proportion, more Python tools are available from PyPI than R tools from Bioconductor/CRAN. My gut feel is this is largely because of the stricter acceptance criteria for the R repositories.

Relatively few tools are available from central software repositories. About 12% from @Bioconductor, 6% from CRAN and 16% from PyPI. Together this is about a third, most of the rest are only available from @github. https://t.co/tXfDu4Jw2y

#RStats  and #Python remain the most common platforms* for developing scRNA-seq tools. More than 10% use C++ but these are mostly R packages seeking some extra performance. A small but consistent community continues to MATLAB.* Tools can use more than one platform https://t.co/1FAEHWUl6p

Most of these tools have a peer-reviewed publication (~70%). Of those that don't ~20% have a preprint and < 10% have no associated reference. More on preprints below. https://t.co/KBBGz0mGZa

A short note of criteria for the database. To be included a tool must 1) show how it can be used to analyse scRNA-seq data and 2) be available to install and use locally. There are some edge cases we try to stick to this if we can.

The first figure provides an overview of the current state of the database. This plot shows the number of tools over time. It's not quite exponential but there's a nice quadratic fit. If this continues we can expect 1500 tools by the end of 2022 and 3000 by the end of 2025. https://t.co/wkPyc3ru1z

Why so little transparency? Good question. All I can say for certain is that the net effect is to mask (get it? haha?) the consequences of decisions being made by locally elected officials and their appointees at the district level. (10/10)

Of course, they won’t divulge how many cases there are each day, just that they were made aware of “a COVID-19 positive case/cases” in the school. The weekly, district-wide updates put an upper limit on it, but there is very, very little transparency here. (9/n)

The good news is that they also resumed school-level notifications this past Monday. Thus, we can at least get a vague sense for the broader landscape. The bad news is that we’ve received one such e-mail every day since then. Every. Single. Day. (8/n)
That's just a hair under 31% percent of *days*, so roughly 1-in-3 days with *at least* one known classroom contact, sometimes more. (7/n)

Meanwhile, we received *two* separate notifications that someone in one of our son’s classes tested positive today. That means that we’ve received 5 such notifications across 4 of 13 schools days so far this year. (6/n)

Incidentally… Last week’s district update has disappeared from the web. It seems that @OconeeCoSchools has either overwritten or deleted the previous week’s update. If one was interested on making it more difficult to track the data, this would be a good approach. (5/n)

But hey, at least people are being allowed to “choose” to wear them. Gee, thanks. And hey, at least they’re requiring a meningitis vaccine (per an email dated 7/26) despite ignoring the availability of a vaccine for a far more immediate public health threat… (4/n)

We also show that three conserved mutational processes, including the two human clock-like signatures, dominate the somatic mutation landscape across all these species. [6/] https://t.co/dl6JXVanII

The data have exceeded all our expectations. We find that somatic mutation rates tightly anticorrelate with lifespan across mammals; a ~50-year-old prediction from the somatic mutation theory of ageing. [5/] https://t.co/GqpXug0rjO

The question of how somatic mutation rates vary across species has attracted theoretical speculation for decades, for its implications for the evolution of cancer and ageing. E.g. See Kirkwood & Holliday, 1979. https://t.co/a7nlSINgPa [4/] https://t.co/G9o6vTqhM6

Here we use laser microdissection of individual intestinal crypts and whole genome sequencing to provide an unprecedented description of the somatic mutation landscape across 16 mammalian species. [3/] https://t.co/fVBHb7yjRr

Accurately measuring somatic mutation rates is technically very challenging and has only been possible in the last few years. Despite some early pioneering work, we currently know very little about it outside of humans. [2/]

Take homes for me on public understanding of genetics. When geneticists use the word predict, there are a lot of riders (small print if you like) wrapped up in this word. Predict is nowhere near "fool proof" or "all settings" and absolutely does not mean we understand why >>
And, unlike plants and farm animals, we're not going to just "wing it" with humans on the "well, it might do something, so we will make the change and see what happens". This is WRONG.

Having diverted through animal and plant genetics, back to human; although people do use the word "predict" for genetic results, with some validity (remembering this "context" thing), this is "predict given people I've seen" not "predict if I make this DNA change".

What these models can't do (one needs quite different models) is predict "if I change this precise part of the genome, what will happen" - this is a ... far harder question, and often only answerable by actually doing it (and guessing some sensible places to change).

and the other very useful prediction is "the consequence of mating these two lines of wheat will give rise to a spread of offspring, some of which will produce high yields [*]" - [*] being the model's context for the farm ("average European wheat field").

And its important to understand farm animal and plant genetic prediction; the prediction is more "if I give you a series of Xs across this cow's genome I can predict how much milk it will produce [*]" - [*] being the model's own context for a farm ("average US diary farm")

This is best seen in much of farm animal and plant genetics  - probably the most "predictive" application of genetics; which, despite using DNA measurements (the X's above) immediately create a pedigree like measurement that absolutely ignore the precise changes of X.

"Which genetic variation near the X I estimated was correlated with the phenotype would I need to change to get the effect I predict". This "prediction of an experiment" is v. v. different to "prediction if you happen to have inherited this chunk".

We only (basically) need one X (genetic variable) per chunk (haplotype) to estimate (the chunks are big but they don't always break in the same place, so it is a complex world down there) but the absolute key thing is we don't know the result of the experiment

In fact, we don't know *why* each X which we associate to (say) measures of intelligence works in the cohorts we have in the context to give rise, even when they are genetic - this is because genomes (human genome in particular) gets inherieted in chunks and these chunks are big
...BUT... THIS IS REALLY WRONG...

Getting beyond the niceities of the model, just by being "predictive" many people read that we could "optimise" or "design" (and some people race ahead here with CRISPR and other things to ... designer babies). This is one reading of the word "predict".
(we can ask this question partly using the genetics of schizophrenia, and the answer is this is part of, but nowhere near the whole story of this).

<< we know for example there are people with very debilitating diseases, such as say schizophrenia, present the world over and running in families; just the unfortunate people who suffer this disease might "explain" this prediction.

Twitter is a great platform for discussion. Discussion implies disagreements, but those can easily escalate to the point of extreme toxicity, affecting peoples' real life. Thus, however heated the debate, please try to remember there's a person behind any (non-bot) account.8/

@skepticalzebra is an interesting case. She's an educated, independent, successful and eloquent woman. She's very smart and systematically wins any argument. For this probably, she's gone under the skin of some big-ego covid twitterati. It didn't help she got a blue tick.7/

@sailorrooscout just waxes lyrical about vaxxes, and tries to convince as many people as she can to get jabbed, with remarkable success. The abuse she got is baffling, even more so given that it came solely from people identifying as pro-vaccine.6/

The worst abuse I've witnessed on twitter was against @sailorrooscout and @skepticalzebra. I find both instances puzzling as both are kind, empathetic, measured people who probably never made any outrageous statement that could reasonably be considered as irresponsible.5/

3. Coordinating smear campaigns and twitter pile-ons is never OK, whether it happens off, or on twitter. Also, when someone's getting already a lot of abuse for a minor infringement, I suggest avoiding adding yet another nasty comment identical to those made by others before.4/

2. A snarky remark targeted at someone's post can be hurtful, but it's something most of us can cope with. Repeating the same point hundreds of times - even more so when targeting the person rather than something they stated at some point - is harassment, which is uncool.3/

1. Twitter is kind of designed for misunderstandings (I've been there a few times). Though, once it's becoming clear that the horrid thing that someone said actually wasn't that horrid - or it was horrid indeed but they deleted their offending tweet - please move on.3/

So, I'm no saint. This being out of the way, there are things I can't condone, I've never engaged in, and would never entertain doing. Given how toxic covid epi-twitter has become, I will list three things that we should all refrain from, and call out when we come across.2/

I'm still learning about the puts-and-takes of the WGS approach and what innovations on the hardware, chemistry, and informatics sides may enable the approach and bring it (hopefully) closer to a reality.

These aren't deal-killers, per se, but they're problematic nonetheless ~ potentially resulting in flipped base-calls and/or sequence context-specific coverage gaps.On the back-end, there'd be gobs more data to interpret, store, and activate on behalf of patients.

I'll end by cautioning that implementing blood-based WGS isn't a walk in the park. On the front-end, even though PCR errors would disappear, SRS still generates two layers of error:1. PCR-like, on-instrument cluster generation2. SBS-specific systematic error

So, it's vital that labs make the best with whatever they start with. When he was still at @freenome, @ImranSHaque gave a great presentation on the dynamics here, especially in support of a truly multi-omic approach to this problem. https://t.co/RY8fswr693

I'm sure there are unique issues and challenges here too. However, now more than ever, I'm convinced that blood-based WGS is a necessary addition for the most competitive liquid biopsy players. Liquid biopsies are limited by the number of molecules in a tube of blood.

We show that one can infer the magnitude of intrinsic, extrinsic, and measurement noises of gene expression solely based on time-resolved data of protein concentration, without any a priori knowledge of the underlying gene expression dynamics. https://t.co/cMy0uCnERY

Considering the time trajectory of protein concentration as a random walker in the concentration space, an effective restoring force (with a corresponding “spring constant”) must exist to prevent the divergence of concentration due to random fluctuations. https://t.co/mq4kID69z2

Please understand that this decision was not made lightly; the organizers incredibly heartbroken over this. However, to protect the community we love, and maintain the experience of this meeting, we feel we have no choice but to forgo this year’s meeting meet again in Sept 2022.

LAMG is known as a very special meeting that includes 5 days of close interactions and networking. Even with strict safety measures or pursuing virtual options, this would take away from much of what makes the LAMG meeting truly special, and therefore we have opted to postpone.

With the Delta variant surging across the globe, lack of access to vaccines, and inequitable travel restrictions, the organizers feel that the only decision one can make is to not pursue an in-person meeting at this time. For those already registered, refunds are being processed.

After careful consideration and many conversations among the organizers, speakers, and registrants, it is with heavy hearts that the LAMG organizing committee has made the difficult decision to postpone this year’s meeting to September 11-15, 2022.

Addition of Bxa to epithelial cells remodeled the actin cytoskeleton & induced secretion of inosine which bxa-encoding Bacteroides can use as a sole carbon source. Using mouse models, we discovered this aids gut colonization & adherence of Bacteroides to epithelial cells. (3/4)

We did an in-depth characterization of an abundant ADP-ribosyltransferase in Bacteroides, Bxa. We discovered Bxa is a secreted protein which binds to host lipid rafts to enter the host epithelial cells and targets non-muscle myosin II. (2/4)

Anyone else doing sth like this? I'd love to see your workflow.
This is not really task management, but capturing the thinking and excitement behind tasks we generate. To help motivate future us get them done.
Often, we do great thinking during a brainstorm. We come up with awesome ideas and turn them into tasks.After a few days, we forget why we were so excited.
The context has been really helpful to future me, who's always feeling resentful of obligation, imposed by past me.

Instead of a laundry list of context-less obligations in a task manager...I write a project note in Craft, writing to myself (and future me who'll forget why these tasks seemed so important) what I want to do and why I want to do it.For example -- https://t.co/jvI0kzfsG9
I've been experimenting with using @craftdocsapp to drive my projects forward.

I am so proud of the work that @KhoreoMag does, of all the stories that we have helped bring to the world, but I am especially grateful that Anjali trusted us with this one and that we are able to be its home. 💚 It was such a pleasure working together!

Standing next to the monument, Manhattan bustling around me without pausing to acknowledge that it was treading on the bones of men, women, and children, was a haunting experience.If you can visit, please do. If you can't, learn more here: https://t.co/yBS0mYqRhY

A few weeks later, I went to see the African Burial Ground National Monument for the first time. In 1991, the "Negroes Buriel Ground", containing over 15,000 skeletal remains of enslaved and free Africans from the 17th and 18th c., was excavated in downtown NYC.

The first time I read it, I spent a few minutes staring out the window of our Manhattan apartment, first making sure that the city was still there—and then just feeling the weight of Anjali's beautiful and shattering words. I haven't stopped thinking about it since.

I had the immense honour of editing "Our Bones Were the Mortar" by @anjapatel. It's out on khōréō's website and podcast today, and if you're going to read one short story this week, please make it this one. As just 1,200 words, it's devastating and so, so important. https://t.co/qyto8TVhlI

Ideally each population would have turnover of varieties every few years as I find better seedlings in each generation.

I won't taste test any of the new seedlings this fall. Instead I'll store them for planting in spring. Next year they should produce enough to try eating some.My goals are increased production in each line, as well as maintaining the disease resistance I've already achieved.

Some of those didn't make it into their 3rd (this) year, so there are about four or so varieties from that first generation still in play.This year I grew a 2nd generation from each of those populations. After an early season beetle catastrophe, I have 3 seedlings from each.

Most of the plants I grew in my 1st generation succumbed to fungus or oomycete pathogens. Some didn't survive winter storage. Some didn't produce enough. Some didn't taste good.After all that I had several varieties which fell into the two categories I described above.

Specifically, I ordered a seed mix from https://t.co/a3wLMZt4jH & have been working from there.I have two populations, selected to different targets from that original diverse mix.The 1st have smaller spuds with distinctly black skin. The 2nd were chosen for high production.

A plea to stay away from the extremes. We're clearly in a better place (at least in the developed world) due to vaccines. We've clearly got a worse enemy, but one we understand pretty well. We've got to play this game out well with vaccines, and get vaccines across the planet.

<< healthcare has to cope with whatever the pandemic throws at them - they are the last line of defence, the final backstop and they continue to work through in many places just the flow of people who have this nasty disease. In that there are great stories of - frankly - heroism

5. I have genuine sympathy that this is still all front page news but it seems to move so slowly - one wants to find new things to talk about. My advice here I think is to at least balance scary stories with good stories - the good stories are often healthcare >>
Other things that help include wearing masks, and not hanging out closely with other people (in particular inside).

as we get there, every bit of transmission we reduce is broadly a good thing. The easiest way to reduce transmission is to be in fresh air - good ventilation - this can be low tech (outdoor lunch, open windows) to high tech (fancy ventilation system) - air exchange is the key.

4. What we need to do is now simple to state but still a long road - vaccinate everyone *in the world* at risk (crudely, >50, but a bit more nuanced) + vaccinate or tolerate infection for the rest of the world. Vaccination is far better than infection until you get to the young

(this is how coronaviruses roll; in humans we have 4 endemic - circulating - coronaviruses, one of which looks like it caused the "Russian 'flu" in Europe of 1888/9. They are one of the types of viruses which gives "the common cold" and responsible for viral pneumonia in the old)

This is why most virologists / infectious epidemiologists I know, and myself (for what it is worth) think the stable end point of the pandemic is some level of endemic (circulating virus) in which SARS-CoV-2 will be nastiest of the coronaviruses that we live with.

One v. frustrating (but unsurprising) thing is that some people who are double vaccinated can still catch and pass on Coronavirus. We don't really understand why this happens, but it does, and the vaccines are performing at the high end of expectations.

3. Vaccination changes the game, but it is not full time/slam dunk/walk away with the win. It is more like two red cards against the coronavirus (football analogy - english style), but we still need to field our team, play well, ie we've still got to navigate this period.

7. Very excited to apply SCITO-seq for population scale immunophenotyping and perturbational screens. An amazing collaboration with @BioLegend and @SpitzerLab. Repos for the tool (https://t.co/6ZpCCc1wis) and paper (https://t.co/26GXoep7px) are on GitHub.
6. SCITO-seq is also compatible with scifi-RNA-seq by utilizing a second bridge oligo to obtain RNA and protein data from the same cell using combinatorial indexing. https://t.co/ED2j60OVF8

5. In addition to increasing cell throughput, pool barcodes can be used to label samples for multiplexing. The plots below show the correlation of surface protein expression and cellular composition between profiling using 60 custom or 165 TotalSeq-C antibodies across 10 samples. https://t.co/9W1b4WYiiE
4. In the revision, we show SCITO-seq can process 175k cells in a single channel of the 10x Chromium instrument and is compatible with the BioLegend TotalSeq-C 165-plex kit. https://t.co/juS9ZoTYIX
3. We implemented SCITO-seq using a splint oligo design that's compatible with a number of conjugation strategies and 10x Genomics chemistries. https://t.co/4JD8C0N2c1

2. For the statistically and computationally inclined, we derived with @yun_s_song closed-form expressions for the collision rate and empty droplet rate of 2-round combinatorial indexing using droplets: https://t.co/OJ3upLwV70.

1. Key to SCITO-seq is to use the massive number of droplets produced by microfluidic devices for 2-round combinatorial indexing. This allows for >100k cell throughput with <100 pool barcodes. Similar in principle to @JD_Buenrostro's dsciATAC-seq & @BockLab's scifi-rna-seq. https://t.co/0QJnLKhXl5

Check out the published version of SCITO-seq in @naturemethods: https://t.co/wzSaD1Y8WI developed by @byungjinhwang and David Lee. SCITO-seq uses combinatorial indexing for surface protein and multimodal profiling of >100k cells in a single microfluidic channel. Highlights 👇

So.... Ethnicity is associated with a little bit genetics inherently (visible characterisitics) and depressingly alot of recent ancestry *via* the social stratification that associated with ethnicity, but this doesn't make ethnicity a crude proxy for genetics.
In fact, I think in human genetics there is far less "genetic background" a la laboratory mouse/maize land races/farm animal genetics but this needs more words than a tweet!)
This deserves its own thread, but the simple answer; given the elephant in the room of social stratification we have to be conservative, and accept we will "model out" some "real" genetic background.

(I can sense some of my genetics colleagues now saying 'well what about genetic background, from "real" epistasis through to background linear polygenic scores? Surely *some* of this PCA selection/PCA covariates are modelling this?  >>
It also gives us smoother LD properties and some other nice features, but for me this is secondary to the "elephant in the room" which is social stratification.

No, we're not. We're using (recent) continental ancestry to predict the *social environment* that people experience in our societies, and making using that the genetics we do our association studies with are randomised to these large societal differences.
Back to my conversation - given geneticists do these sorts of subselections in their analysis,  are we not saying there is *something* in the genetics of continental groupings / continental ancestry?
We welcome feedback from genetics and non-genetics colleagues on how best to craft our language to explain what we're doing.

It is clunky, but we suggest using more technical precise terms (eg, first usage, "The European-associated PCAcluster, which aims to minimise variation in non-genetic factors and genetic factors" ; repeated usage "PCA-selected European subset"

but at least it hits the right notes.As authors are usually also editors and reviewers, I am curious to whether I am too rigid here, or not rigid enough, am I worrying about nothing?Open for debate.#editor #peerreview #journals #confidentiality

I know there are publishers/journals/submission systems that do it properly, i.e. asking permission for a) transferring the review and separately b) transferring information on the reviewers identity.It could still be better (indicating that such consent can be withdrawn) 12/n

But shouldn't that go both ways, i.e. "journals should respect the confidentiality of the peer review process"? Transferring review reports and reviewer identities to other journals, even within the same series looks to me like disrespecting the confidentiality. 11/n

https://t.co/yDmwxqqgZtThe other side of the coin has been extensively discussed, about open peer review and whether people have the right to publish the review reports they have written, via @C0PE . "reviewers should respect the confidentiality of the peer review process" 10/n

What about journals/publishers that just share it without asking for consent. Maybe they never thought about it, but is that an excuse? Facebook/Twitter etc should have made people more aware about privacy and confidentiality. 9/n

If I notice it, I would automatically suspect bad intentions and not give any consent whatsoever, plus I would consider not reviewing again for that journal/series. Bad choice. But at least they give the option, there is worse. 8/n

That is an opt-out approach and is not informative of where it can be shared with, and how to withdraw consent. In general I would say that an Opt-Out approach is usually chosen because of laziness and never for good intentions. I hate Opt-out. 7/n

https://t.co/7SRDeSNNU4So how does that work? I had a look at @BioMedCentral policies, that's a no for me. It says "Reviewers who do not wish us to share their report with another BMC journal should indicate this in the confidential section of their report." 6/n

My view is that no such transfer can ever be done without informed consent, and that this consent can be declined, and also can be withdrawn at a later stage. It does not give the journals freedom to transfer, and then maybe transfer again and again. 5/n

But what about the review reports/reviewer identity? There is something to say about not wasting reviewer effort, so that the reports are transferred. But should that be with reviewer identity, so the new handling editors can judge their expertise? 4/n
